s\u0026rsquo;, and the trail remains the most popular of the routes today.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp style=\"text-align:justify\"\u003eRunning along the eastern and western coasts of the Kii peninsula are the Iseji route and Kiiji route, respectively. The Kiiji route historically connected Kyōto and Ōsaka to the Three Grand Shrines of Kumano, linking up with the Nakahechi route at Tanabe City. Meanwhile, the Iseji route connects Ise Grand Shrine, the holiest place in the Shintō religion, with the Grand Shrines of Kumano.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ctable align=\"center\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"width:90%\"\u003e\n\t\u003ctbody\u003e\n\t\t\u003ctr\u003e\n\t\t\t\u003ctd style=\"text-align: center;\"\u003e\u003cimg alt=\"\" height=\"200\" src=\"https://static-oku.diqit.io/uploads/oku/kumanokodo1-1667893688781.jpg\" style=\"margin:auto;\" width=\"300\" /\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\t\t\t\u003ctd style=\"text-align: center;\"\u003e\u003cimg alt=\"\" height=\"200\" src=\"https://static-oku.diqit.io/uploads/oku/dsc05701-2-1667893764724.jpg\" style=\"margin:auto;\" width=\"300\" /\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\t\t\t\u003ctd style=\"text-align: center;\"\u003e\u003cimg alt=\"\" height=\"200\" src=\"https://static-oku.diqit.io/uploads/oku/img_9381-1667893993098.jpg\" style=\"margin:auto;\" width=\"300\" /\u003e\u003c/td\u003e\n\t\t\u003c/tr\u003e\n\t\u003c/tbody\u003e\n\u003c/table\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2 style=\"text-align:center\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-size:20px\"\u003eHighlights of The Kumano Kodō Trail\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp style=\"text-align:justify\"\u003eIts isolation from the rest of Japan truly lends the Kumano Kodō an immense sense of calm, complemented by its striking scenery, the delicious food and the warmth of its locals. Being close to the Pacific coast, the region is also famous for its tuna dishes, and local pilgrims will be well acquainted with the revitalising power of \u003cem\u003emeharizushi\u003c/em\u003e \u0026ndash; salted rice balls wrapped in mustard leaves. Be it for a journey of self-discovery, a pilgrimage of worship, or simply for the joy of the hike, the Kumano Kodō is a must-visit location for a walking tour in Japan.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n\t\u003cli style=\"text-align:justify\"\u003eWalk the Nakahechi as it weaves a path to the three grand shrines: Hongū Grand Shrine, shaded beneath the towering tree canopy of Hongū; Nachi Grand Shrine and its iconic vermillion pagoda set against the backdrop of Nachi Falls; and Hayatama Grand Shrine in Shingū, which sits alongside the gentle waters of the Kumano River.\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli style=\"text-align:justify\"\u003eTake steps towards your dual pilgrim certification. The Kumano Kodō \u0026ndash; inclusive of its grand shrines and the pilgrimage routes that join them \u0026ndash; was granted UNESCO World Heritage status in July of 2004, joined only by the Camino de Santiago de Compostela in Spain as pilgrimage routes to be awarded this status. Our classic Kumano Kodō self-guided walking tours and our Kiiji self-guided walking tours qualify you for this coveted status!\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli style=\"text-align:justify\"\u003eWalk the Kiiji route, the original approach to the Kumano Kodo. Take in the remote west coast of the Kii-Peninsula before weaving into the classic Nakahechi route as you head inland to the atmospheric forests the trail is known for.\u0026nbsp;\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli style=\"text-align:justify\"\u003eVisit Ise Grand Shrine, the holiest site in the religion of Shintō, with travellers who come from around the country to make their pilgrimmage.\u003c/li\u003e\n\t\u003cli style=\"text-align:justify\"\u003eHike the Iseji route, a breathtaking combination of coastal walks and quiet mountain paths, connecting some of the most sacred sites of the region.\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n","hightlight":"","information":"","secure_safe":"","type":1,"level":{"1":{"thumbnail":"","text":""},"2":{"thumbnail":"","text":""},"3":{"thumbnail":"","text":""},"4":{"thumbnail":"","text":""}},"is_active":1,"is_delete":0,"created_at":"2022-08-05T01:58:31.705Z","updated_at":"2024-04-02T02:21:52.509Z","created_by":"","updated_by":"","subtitle":"","region":2},{"uuid":"0b79844d-c4b8-442d-9c31-718c7c2100f5","name":"Northern Japan","code":"IBNorthernJapan","slug":"northern-japan","sequence":3,"thumbnail":"https://static-oku.diqit.io/uploads/oku/destination-translate-thumbnail/img_6509.jpg","overview":"","gallery":[{"name":"IMG_6509.jpg","url":"https://static-oku.diqit.io/uploads/oku/destination-translate-gallery/img_6509.jpg","focal":{"x":50,"y":50}},{"name":"JMS9-s.jpg","url":"https://static-oku.diqit.io/uploads/oku/destinations/jms9s-1662688500761.jpg","focal":null},{"name":"JMS2-s.jpg","url":"https://static-oku.diqit.io/uploads/oku/destinations/jms2s-1662688482678.jpg","focal":null},{"name":"Nikko-summer.jpg","url":"https://static-oku.diqit.io/uploads/oku/destination-translate-gallery/nikkosummer.jpg","focal":{"x":50,"y":50}}],"short_description":"\u003cp\u003eNorthern Japan, collectively known as the Tōhoku region, connects Tōkyō in the south-east with the island of Hokkaidō in the north. The area itself is coated in forest and mountain with most of the population concentrated within the lowlands.\u003c/p\u003e\n","long_description":"\u003ch2 style=\"text-align:center\"\u003e\u003cspan style=\"font-size:20px\"\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eYAMAGATA, FUKUSHIMA, AKITA AND MORE\u003c/strong\u003e\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp style=\"text-align:justify\"\u003e\u0026nbsp;\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp style=\"text-align:justify\"\u003eNorthern Japan, collectively known as the\u0026nbsp;Tōhoku\u0026nbsp;region, connects Tōkyō in the south-east with the island of Hokkaidō in the north. The area itself is coated in forest and mountain with most of the population concentrated within the lowlands. As such, the region features six of Japan\u0026#39;s most rural prefectures; from\u0026nbsp;Yamagata\u0026nbsp;to\u0026nbsp;Aomori\u0026nbsp;to the very north of Honshū. Sitting higher on the northern hemisphere, Tōhoku experiences cooler summer temperatures but also harsher winters. With the advent of the \u003cem\u003eshinkansen\u003c/em\u003e bullet train and a great range of domestic airports, it is simple to travel to all six of Tōhoku\u0026#39;s prefectures either on land or by air. For example, you can reach\u0026nbsp;Shin-Aomori\u0026nbsp;station from Tōkyō station in roughly three hours \u0026ndash; a distance of nearly 700 km. From there, regional trains and buses reach out across the region, allowing visitors and residents to travel around easily from town to town.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ctable align=\"center\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"width:90%\"\u003e\n\t\u003ctbody\u003e\n\t\t\u003ctr\u003e\n\t\t\t\u003ctd\u003e\u003cimg alt=\"\" height=\"200\" src=\"https://static-oku.diqit.io/uploads/oku/000000982-1666833213399.jpg\" width=\"300\" /\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:rgba(220,220,220,0.5)\"\u003e\u003cimg alt=\"\" height=\"15\" src=\"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAPABAP///wAAACH5BAEKAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw==\" width=\"15\" /\u003e\u003c/span\u003e​\u003c/td\u003e\n\t\t\t\u003ctd\u003e\u003cimg alt=\"\" height=\"200\" src=\"https://static-oku.diqit.io/uploads/oku/00000167-1666833151338.jpg\" width=\"300\" /\u003e\u003cspan style=\"background-color:rgba(220,220,220,0.5)\"\u003e\u003cimg alt=\"\" height=\"15\" src=\"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAPABAP///wAAACH5BAEKAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw==\" width=\"15\" /\u003e\u003c/span\u003e​\u003c/td\u003e\n\t\t\t\u003ctd\u003e\u003cimg alt=\"\" height=\"200\" src=\"https://static-oku.diqit.io/uploads/oku/walking-1666833264287.jpg\" width=\"300\" /\u003e\u003cspan style=\"